segments.text: April 1, 1976.
This is Tommy Moorhead, 9-11 Lazy Lane, Bryan, Texas, by Roger Ferguson as part of an oral history project, the Bryan College Station area.
Tommy, how long have you been in this area?
I was born and raised here, so in June it will be 23 years.
23 years.
How about your descendants?
How long have they been in this area?
On my mother's side, for as long as we know of, I know for a fact that my great-grandfather homesteaded here in the Steep Hollow area.
We have some proof that they were here in this general area.
I don't know exactly where since prior to the Civil War.
We've got letters that have been sent back to some of our relatives that we've kept from that day.
Why did they come to this area?
why they chose this particular area to settle in?
They were homesteaders looking for land.
They were primarily farmers and chose the St. Paul area right outside what is today Brown and College Station as prime farmland and decided to settle there.
So they were mostly farmers, is that right?
That's correct.
Later on, though, my grandfather was in the dairy business when my mother was a child.
And
raised dairy cattle and sold milk in the general area here.
How about your ancestry?
Moorhead, what kind of name is that?
Moorhead is Indian.
My father's from East Texas.
He didn't come to this area until 1946, although he did have some relatives here earlier.
In fact, his aunt, who is my great-aunt,
was the first woman sheriff in Texas.
Oh, really?
Her husband, who was named Leonard Moorhead, who my father is named after, was sheriff here in the early 1900s.
And at one time, he had caught a fugitive and had him sent to prison.
And in the courtroom, the...
person stood up in court and vowed that he would get my uncle.

And so later on he had been sent to an insane asylum and he escaped from there and was out at the old steep hall of church one night and snuck up in the bushes and put a pistol up to the window and shot my uncle in the head and killed him.
That's not really funny.
I know it's not.
It's a bit unusual though.
Anyway, he killed my uncle and my aunt, whose name she remarried later and may be found in some of the documents of history that are in brine today.
Her name was changed to Lila Withers later on.
And Aunt Lila swore out revenge on this particular person and loaded up a posse and went out and captured him and brought him back into town and he was
sent away once again to stay.
And my aunt took over and filled my uncle's shoes as sheriff of Rhyne and became the first woman sheriff in the state of Texas and then was later elected in her own right to be sheriff of the town.
She tells a lot of stories.
She just died about a year ago now in her mid-90s, I guess it was.
And she used to tell me stories as a child of, she was sheriff during Prohibition
And she would go down the streets of Bryan and confiscate all the whiskey that was being bootlegged and pour it down the streets of Bryan, as she said.
So they all liked her pretty well?
I mean, she didn't meet with any resistance for being a woman sheriff?
No, in fact, I guess you could say she was one of the first women's laborers.
But she enjoyed being a sheriff.
enjoyed it quite a lot.
She liked law enforcement.
And the women and men of the town accepted her as such.
And she did a very fine job.

Right before she died, about five years ago, she was honored in Bryan and received a plaque and a medal and everything, showing that she was the first woman sheriff and that the historians of the town did appreciate her contributions to the city.
That's pretty interesting that
they would accept her so readily.
It seems like all the people at Bryan and College Station are somewhat on the conservative side.
You know, a woman's place is in the home.
Is that basically, would you say, the character of most people that live in Bryan?
Would you say it's a conservative area?
Yes, very much so, particularly Bryan more so than College Station.

I think a lot has to do with the College Station, the education influence and the vast mobility of the people in College Station tends to make it a more liberal area, whereas Bryan is a more conservative area.

I know when I went to school here, you could tell that by the school systems, that Bryan was a much more conservative school, say for instance, just in their dress code, whereas College Station's dress code wasn't nearly as defined as Bryan's was.
In fact, they even slipped to not even having one, I believe, during the later years.
You graduated from A&M, is that right?
Yes, in 75.
And what was your degree in?
English and history with a teaching certificate education.
A teaching certificate.
Do you know much about the educational facilities or early education programs in Bryan College Station areas?
Not a whole lot.
I know in talking with my mother when she was growing up, she's now
in her late 40s.
And when she was a young child, for instance, they did have country schools out in St. Paula and around the surrounding communities.
And in fact, she even had to start school a year early because she was the only one her age.
And they didn't want to have just one person in first grade.
So she had to start at age five and go in with all the six year olds.
I know Fannin, which is now an elementary school, used to be the high school.
In fact, she graduated from Stephen F. Austin, although it was in the Fannin building at that time.
The new high school in Bryan, was that built when you graduated from there?
Did you graduate from Bryan High?
No, I graduated from Stephen F. Austin.
From Stephen F. Austin.
I was in the last graduating class in May of 71 from Stephen F. Austin.
Then we integrated after that, and Kemp was the black high school and Seminole-Austin the white, and we integrated and joined forces at Brown High.
And joined forces.
Did that particular integration, did you have any problems?
Like, say, you know, the big race riots in Houston.
How did the people here take the integration of the schools?
with mixed emotions, I guess I could say.

I don't know if it was directly from the integration itself, but I know that the school system as a whole, the teaching of the material and everything, or the material that has been taught, has lowered.
And the standards, I think, of our education have been lowered by a deal.
I don't think it's nearly as good as it used to be.
That's interesting.
Are there any particular reasons?
I mean, you know, why you don't think it's as good as it used to be?
Did they just slow the whole process down, or, you know, can you say?
Well, I really don't know.
I know I went back and taught for a while after I graduated, but I don't know if it's completely to do with the integration or not,
But I know the whole attitudes of the students have changed.
It may just, quote, unquote, the new generation, although I hate to think that a new generation is coming up and I'm getting that old.
But now we don't have dress codes.
The kids can come to school as long as they're not indecently exposed.
And I think that takes away from the rigidness of a school system.
And it's not all bad, but yet at the same time, I like the more formal education.
Maybe it's because of my conservative upbringing from this area.
How about you personally?
Do you have any particular reason for choosing the Bryan College Station area you need to live in?
I really didn't choose when I was born into it.
Do you ever feel like you'd like to get out?
Yes, I'd like to continue my education and get my master's.
So my master's should be finished in May of 77.
And I do think that I would like to move and become, I want to stay in the university system since I've been here and I've got my assistantship working in student affairs.
And I'd like to be a
somewhere working either as an assistant dean of students or somewhere in student personnel work at some other university, but I think that I need to get away and get some new and different ideas.
It is a good town.
I may eventually come back here, but still being young and single, as I might say, I would like to do a little bit of exploring on my own.
From your study of the Bryan College Stationery
Do you know of any particular catastrophes or tragedies, anything like this that's happened that might be interesting?
Well, in the early years, I know we've had pneumonia epidemics that killed out a lot of people and things like this.
But in my own lifetime, I can remember...
what we call the big fire, which was the Montgomery Ward building downtown burned.
I can't remember the exact year.
It was probably in the early 60s.
It burned, and to me it seemed like that was the first step in the death of downtown Bryan because this was the first major move.
The fire was, there was no way to control it,
Everybody in the town just stood around and watched it burn.
It was a huge building.
In fact, the lot is still vacant.
There was nothing ever rebuilt there.
And Montgomery Ward's moved out to where it is now.
And Manor is small.
And I think that was the coming of the malls and the beginning of the death for downtown of towns and cities.
Were there ever any days where the downtown of Bryan was the teeming sub-metropolis, I guess you'd say, like you see in the movies?
you know, of, like, gun smoke.
You know, can you visualize that?
You mean way back in history?
Yeah.
Oh, yeah, I've got pictures from my grandparents.
And I can remember my grandparents talking about loading up the wagon.
And it took forever, I guess, in a wagon.
I know that right now they're about five miles out of the city limit, but I guess to downtown Brine it would be about...
10 miles or so, and I guess it did take quite a long time to come into town.
But we've got pictures where the wagons and the people are just all over the streets of Brown.
And even as a kid, before we went to this mall system that I think our society has gone to with the various stores at different locations in the city, as a child, downtown was the place to go.
That's where all the stores were.
You had your local drug store that had its soda fountain.
You had the Woolworth's store and just everything focused around downtown.
I noticed some of the buildings in the Bryan downtown area are fairly old buildings.
Do you know anything about the architecture of the area or any particular buildings in the history of Bryan College Station that would be interesting?
I know that, okay, like,
Some of the banks had some of the old buildings.

If I'm correct in thinking, I think that the City National Bank, what's now out on Texas Avenue, and there was a semi-modern bank in downtown Bryan, and if I'm correct in my thinking, they also had one of the old buildings.
I believe it's where ANCO Insurance is now, and you can still see engraved on the building in the stonework the name of the bank.
Talking about architecture, though, there's an interesting story that my dad has told me that there are two very large, well, there were two very large homes here called the Aston States.
One of them that a lot of people might know was WC's on Texas Avenue.
It was an old estate that was turned into a club.
The Aston brothers came here years and years ago
and sort of made a rivalry between the two brothers just to see who could build a better house.
And one Aston estate was on Texas Avenue, and the other Aston estate is back on 25th Street.
And they decided to see who could build the better home.
And in looking at the two, the one on 25th Street won out.
Hands down.
Right.
It was really a fine house.
What was that?
or the professions of the Aston brothers.
Do you know what they did?
They dabbled in a little bit of everything.
In fact, Parker Aston Hardware store that is still here was begun by one of the Aston brothers.
And while we're talking here, I'm thinking of other little stories.
Go out ahead.
Brazos Briscoe, Mr. Briscoe told me this himself.
He was a real good friend of my dad's, and I'm sure anyone that's familiar with the area.
Is this the Briscoe lumber?
Mm-hmm.
They were of Italian descent and raised cotton out in the bottom, and that's where they made most of their money, right there.
Anyway, Mr. Brazos came up.

over here from Italy with very little money and at one time one of the Aston brothers really got on his back and cheated him out for being a no good Italian with no money at all and really gave him a hard time and Mr. Brazos vowed that someday he would own everything that the Aston brothers ever owned and as Mr. Brazos built up his cotton industry and began selling cotton
everything like that, he gradually picked up and bought everything that the Astin brothers ever had, except for one thing.
Mr. Briscoe died very suddenly about five or six years ago, and the only thing that he had lacked buying was the Astin estate over on 25th Street, and it's just because Mrs. Astin had outlived him
And she soon died about six months after Mr. Virisco did.
And the stay has since been taken care of by the trustees at the bank.
That's an interesting story.
You said that Mr. Virisco was Italian.
Is that pretty much a trend?
Were there many Italian immigrants in this area?
Yes, we've got a lot of people of Italian descent.
You can tell by the names, Scamardo, Ruffino, Restivo, Berisco, Scamardo.
We've got them all.
We've got a lot of Italians here.
I think the majority of them were in the cotton industry, which was a very big industry here.
In fact, we've still got a lot of cotton down the bottom today.
We also have a lot of people of Spanish descent, which I'm sure has been
due to people moving out of Mexico and moving north.
Then we've got, like, my mom is Scotch Irish, so we have people of that descent also, and just a whole mixture.
But we do have a strong Italian and Spanish influence here.
You mentioned the fact that the Ashton brothers made a lot of their money in cotton.
And it was one time a thriving business here.
Are there any other businesses that you can think of that were?
Well, Vrisco was the one that made cotton.
Oh, Vrisco was?
Vrisco's the one that made cotton.
Okay.
I'm not really sure where the Aston started.
They may have started cotton also.
But I do know them, like the hardware store and many other things.
And I believe a lumber company also.
Let's see, other industries.
Cotton and farming and cattle primarily, I think, before you get into the more industrial type thing of the 20th century.
Of course, now we've got several industries in more modern times.
You mentioned Lila Withers was a famous person in your background.
Do you have any others?
Maybe not in your particular background, but particular individuals that you know of?
that may have left their mark on the area.
Yeah.
In fact, I've got one relative that I'm very proud of.
I'm sorry you hadn't done a little bit better.
I don't know if you're aware of it or not, but my name is Tommy Lee Moorhead, and the Lee has a very significant purpose for being in my name.
On my mother's side, we are direct descendants from Robert E. Lee,
And one child out of every generation carries the middle name of Lee.
I carry it.
Then my uncle, my mother's older brother, was named Alan Lee.
And then my grandfather's name is Roy Lee.
And it just goes on back.
All the way down.
Were your descendants, well, not your descendants, I guess your predecessors, were they involved in the Civil War?
Did they fight?
I know you mentioned something about your...
You had a letter or something?
Yes.
We were definitely pro-South.
Pro-South.
We were definitely Southerners and rebels.
The war of northern aggression.
Right.
Yes, let's see.
I've got to figure this out now.
We have a letter that was sent to my great-aunt's mother.
So would that be my great-great-aunt?

great-aunts mother yes I don't know it was my great-aunts mother her husband was away fighting in the Civil War and wrote a letter back to her and her oldest daughter at that time we called petty she was just a small baby
and he was writing back saying how much he missed her and everything, how the world was going, and that he missed his wife and Patty very much.
What would you say is the chief means of livelihood for most people in the Bryan College Station area after the farming and ranching of the early years?
What would you say during the 1920s?
during that age around World War I?
We didn't have very much industry as such.
Like so many people were so conscious of the war effort and helping supply things for the war.
But I guess just small businesses and we do still have a lot of cotton and
farming going on around the edges of the community here.
I guess I should say city we're growing so much.
It was a good area for people to get a start.
I know my dad came here without a high school education or high school diploma and was able to start his own store and build it up.
He started in 46 and so he's celebrating his 30th year of business now.
And he's been able to build it up to a corporation and be a very successful businessman
And it was a very good area and very appealing to people that wanted to start out and do something on their own.
What business is your father in?
He's in the glass business.
He has Acme Glass Company incorporated in the area.
You mentioned the war effort and people all geared toward the war.
Do you know anything about this that you could tell us?
Not really specific, so I'm sure that...
I'm talking about World War I or World War II.
It doesn't matter.
Okay, I know they took people, like my grandfather went to World War I. I really don't know if the area did anything for a specific cause except exist and try to make it through both wars.
During the Depression, I know here a lot was done to...
The farmers were the ones that really made out the best and furnished food for other people.

In fact, the farmers, it's similar to the Waltons, I guess you'd say, because they always had plenty to eat, never much money, but plenty to eat, and it was a good time to bargain with the store people with food rather than money.
Kind of switch tables on them.
Mm-hmm.
This year is, as you know, the bicentennial, a lot of celebrations and things going on like that.
Can you remember any celebrations in particular, Bryant area, big shindigs?
Well, unfortunately, this is a very mixed community.
I mean, it's fortunate.
I don't know.

We've got a lot of influence from a lot of different background cultures, but we're not so much like a completely German community like, for instance, New Braunfels has their worst fest and everything.
But I do remember one celebration that was a lot of fun for me as a child.
I was about nine years old, I guess.
I don't remember the exact year.
I should because I've lived here all my life.
But Brian celebrated their centennial.
And you could go to the merchants and get wooden nickels.
And then on one special night, or it was really about a week, I guess, there,
We dressed up in centennial costumes.
One particular day, I can remember, was the official celebration day.
We dressed up in our centennial clothes.
The women wore centennial dresses with the hoops on.
In fact, it was the first time I wore a hoop.
Don't ever try to sit down in a hoop dress.
You end up catching a hoop right in your face.

We dressed up in our, you know, costumes and everything and had a real good time and you could buy things with the wooden nickels and the men had to grow beards and we had a jail out in the street and we had a street dance.
And it was a lot of fun.
People rode their horses in the town.
It was a good, fun celebration.
In fact, I can remember thinking I wish I could be, you know, around
for the next centennial because it seems like I would have gotten more out of it.
However, I've been too old to get very much more out of it.
But it was something that I really had a lot of fun and enjoyed.
It was neat.
You talked about how conservative this area has generally been historically.
What factors can you name or give us that would seem to support this?
Well, the whole South, I think, really is conservative.
Texas is a fairly conservative state, I think.
So that is a lot from where it stems.
In this particular community, though, I think we had two very severe impressions from the standpoint that, okay, we had A&M, which was a military school here,
that started, as everyone well knows, in 1876.
And then also later, later too, we had another military school that was founded by Nat Allen called Allen Military Academy.
And this was not exactly a reformatory school, but it was a military school as such that went from the sixth grade through, it was a, I can remember it being a,
junior college.
It took you to the first two years of college and then a lot of people transferred from Allen over into A&M.
But now it's just from the sixth grade or it changed then from the sixth grade to twelfth grade and now it's just a private school more so than a strict military school.
Where was this located?
It's over in North Bryan, about on 22nd Street, because we lived on 23rd when I was very, very young.
That was when my parents first lived, after they got married.
And it was about four blocks from our house.
It's still there today.
Is it an all-male type?
Mm-hmm.
When it was military.
Now it is open, and it's co-educational.
And it's all grades starting even in elementary school, I believe, now.
It's simply a private school.
And a lot of, I know when we had immigration, a lot of parents put their children into Allen.
But of course, students still come from all over the world and go to Allen Academy.
Speaking of, you know, the educational institutions, of course, the biggest one in this area is college here.
And what...
What effect do you think that the school has had on the Ryan College Station area?
Well, I'm most familiar with the effect that the school has had on the area, I guess, since Earl Rudder was president.
In the past, I know it had a varying effect on the area in the fact that it did supply a nine-month population boom every year.
although it wasn't much back then, but it still was an input of people that helped the businesses in town with their selling of merchandise.
They were good customers to everyone.
But even more so now, I think it has helped make Bryan College Station a spot on the map.
As it changed from a college into a university and became more diversified,
and has grown larger.
It has brought an intense amount of students here.
It's brought a lot of faculty and staff.
It's really helped the community go, not so much from the educational standpoint, but I think a lot, too, from the research that is carried on here.
It's brought a lot of people here into the area.
And as we have more here, I've noticed more industry come in, for example.
like more business forms.
Well, we've had a Linco here for several years.
We've had International Shoe Factory here for years.
A lot of industry is coming into the area.
We've had our industrial park set up in the last three years.
Hold on there.
What's bypassed?
I guess maybe the last ten years, really.
Time seems to fly so much.
I really don't have all my dates straight, but...
It has grown in my lifetime considerably.
I can remember they used to say, in fact, it's still on the street signs.
I think it's supposed to be four or five miles from College Station to Bryan.
I can remember when there was that definite, distinct difference where Piggly Wiggly and A&W Root Beer and all these things used to stand.
It was country.
there weren't businesses and homes everywhere like there are today.
Was Texas Avenue still where it is, though?
Was it still the main road that connected the two?
Yeah, but it used to be a lot skinnier.
Was it paved?
Yeah, well, I'm sure a long time ago it wasn't, but as long as I can remember, it has been paved.
But, for instance, the street that we live on now, which now is right in the heart of a residential area, I can remember more.
